# Project standards

## Stack

- Next.js App Router, React, TypeScript
- Pigment CSS (no Tailwind)
- File-based MDX in `content/` via `src/lib/content.ts`
- Supabase for auth, profiles, and comments
- Jest + React Testing Library for unit/integration tests
- Lighthouse CI for performance checks

## Code

- Prefer TypeScript everywhere; use absolute `@/` imports
- Import order: external → internal (`@/`) → styles
- Functional React only; default to server components; add `'use client'` only when needed
- Follow `CONVENTIONS.md` for directory roles and file naming
- Use domain terms from `docs/glossary.md` (never "Login"/"Logout" in UI or new symbols)
- Make changes but do not create commits unless asked
- Conventional Commits when committing

## Supabase

- RLS enabled on all tables; update `src/lib/db/schema.sql` when schema or policies change
- Do not connect to Supabase or apply migrations automatically — provide SQL for manual application
- Auth/profile mutations live in `src/app/actions/**`

## Testing and quality

- Co-locate tests (`Foo.tsx` → `Foo.test.tsx`)
- Enforce ≥70% coverage via `npm run test:ci` / `scripts/check-coverage.js`
- No silent fallbacks for required data — log and throw (or return an explicit error response)
- Prefer tests at module interfaces over implementation details

## Accessibility and SEO

- Semantic HTML; visible focus; contrast ≥ 4.5:1 (AA)
- Next.js Metadata API for titles, canonicals, and Open Graph

## Styling

- Pigment CSS `styled()`; design tokens from `src/lib/tokens.ts`
- Cross-component styles in `src/styles/`; no raw hex for colors/spacing when a token exists
